  "description": "¶Scope This module covers functional programming as a paradigm for structuring computation. It is concerned with the ideas — pure functions, immutability, composition, higher-order functions, currying — not with any specific language or implementation.\n¶Assumptions Functions are values. The module assumes a computational setting where functions are first-class: they can be passed as arguments, returned as results, and stored in variables. Purity is the default. Lessons treat pure functions as the norm and side effects as the exception. Impure operations (I/O, mutation) exist at the boundaries of a program, not at its core. No specific language. Examples use pseudocode or informal notation. Language-specific details belong in language modules (Haskell, Scheme, etc.), not here. ¶Boundaries Lambda calculus is the mathematical foundation but lives in /mathematics/disciplines/type-theory/. This module uses lambda notation informally; formal treatment belongs there. Type systems (static types, algebraic data types, type inference) are orthogonal to the paradigm. Typed functional programming is important but is covered by type-theory and language-specific modules. Category-theoretic abstractions (functors, monads, natural transformations) are not covered. They build on these foundations but require mathematical prerequisites outside this module\u0026rsquo;s scope. ¶Invariants Every term in terms/ defines exactly one concept and links to related terms within the module. Every lesson in curricula/ declares its prerequisites in requires frontmatter and what it teaches in teaches. Composition of pure functions produces a pure function. This property is assumed throughout and should not need re-derivation in individual lessons. ",
